[{"id":"VR251773","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\"><strong>Read each question carefully. Write your response in the space provided for each part of each question. Answers must be written out in paragraph form. Outlines, bulleted lists, or diagrams alone are not acceptable and will not be scored.</strong></p>\n&nbsp;\n\n<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">In response to an increase in the frequency of thunderstorms that produce damaging hail, some apple growers have started to cover their apple orchards with large nets. While these nets protect the apple trees from hail damage, the nets also decrease the amount of light that reaches the trees. In an attempt to reduce the impact of shading by the nets, researchers investigated the ability of different ground covers placed around the base of the trees to reflect light back to the apple trees. An apple orchard with genetically identical apple trees was divided in half. A reflective ground cover was applied to one half of the orchard, while grass was left as the ground cover for the other half. A sample of apples was taken from every tree. The percent of light reflected by the two ground covers was measured at three distances above the ground (Figure 1).</p>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Figure 1 presents a bar graph. The vertical axis is labeled “Percent of Light Reflected,” and the numbers negative 10 through 70, in increments of 10, are indicated. The following two categories are indicated on the horizontal axis: Grass and Reflective Ground Cover. Each category has three bars, which each have an error bar. A key indicates that one bar represents 0.5 meter, one bar represents 1.0 meter, and one bar represents 1.5 meters. The data are as follows. Note that all values are approximate. Category 1. Grass. 0.5 meter, 7%, with an error bar that extends from negative 4% to 18%. 1.0 meter, 7%, with an error bar that extends from negative 1% to 15%. 1.5 meters, 5%, with an error bar that extends from negative 2% to 12%. Category 2. Reflective Ground Cover. 0.5 meter, 49%, with an error bar that extends from 39% to 59%. 1.0 meter, 40.5%, with an error bar that extends from 31.5% to 49.5%. 1.5 meters, 38%, with an error bar that extends from 30% to 46%.\" height=\"241\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR251773.g03.png\" width=\"200\" /></div>\n\n<p class=\"passage_para\">Figure 1. Percent of light reflected by ground covers, measured at three distances above the ground. Error bars equal <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"plus or minus 2 S E sub x bar\"><math alttext=\"plus or minus 2 S E sub x bar\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mo>±</mo><mn>2</mn><mtext>SE</mtext></mrow><mrow><mover><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>¯</mo></mrow></mover></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">The amount of light that apple trees receive changes the expression of a certain transcription factor. This transcription factor affects the transcription rate of the gene encoding the enzyme phenylalanine ammonium-lyase (<span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P A L\"><math alttext=\"P A L\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>PAL</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>). The <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P A L\"><math alttext=\"P A L\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>PAL</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> enzyme is required for the production of two types of pigments, anthocyanins and flavonoids, which contribute to the coloration of apples. Light also affects the activity of the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P A L\"><math alttext=\"P A L\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>PAL</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> enzyme by a signal transduction pathway (Figure 2).</p>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Figure 2 presents a simplified model of a signal transduction pathway. From left to right, the model begins with P A L Active. A rightward pointing arrow labeled Kinase extends from P A L active to Phosphorylated P A L inactive. A leftward pointing arrow labeled Phosphatase extends from Phosphorylated P A L inactive back to P A L active. An arrow labeled Light points toward Phosphatase. A rightward pointing arrow extends from Phosphorylated P A L inactive to Degradation of P A L. \" height=\"86\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR251773.g01.png\" width=\"398\" /></div>\n\n<p class=\"passage_para\">Figure 2. Simplified model of the signal transduction pathway leading to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P A L\"><math alttext=\"P A L\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>PAL</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> activation and breakdown</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">The researchers measured the average concentrations of anthocyanins and flavonoids in apples from trees grown with both types of ground cover (Table 1).</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"standalone_statement style:1\">TABLE 1. CONCENTRATION OF ANTHOCYANINS AND FLAVONOIDS IN APPLES</p>\n\n<div class=\"table_wrapper\">\n<table class=\"tgroup align:center cols:3 pgwide:1 table_role:presentation\">\n\t<colgroup>\n\t\t<col class=\"colspec colname:col1 colnum:1 colwidth:100\" />\n\t\t<col class=\"colspec colname:col2 colnum:2 colwidth:150\" />\n\t\t<col class=\"colspec colname:col3 colnum:3 colwidth:150\" />\n\t</colgroup>\n\t<tbody class=\"tbody\">\n\t\t<tr class=\"row\">\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col1 text-center\">Type of Pigment</td>\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col2\">\n\t\t\t<p class=\"text-center\">Concentration of Pigment</p>\n\t\t\t<span class=\"formatted_line_break delivery_mode:Both text-center\"></span>\n\n\t\t\t<p class=\"text-center\">(mean <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"plus or minus 2 S E sub x bar\"><math alttext=\"plus or minus 2 S E sub x bar\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mo>±</mo><mn>2</mn><mtext>SE</mtext></mrow><mrow><mover><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>¯</mo></mrow></mover></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> in <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"nanomoles per square centimeter\"><math alttext=\"nanomoles per square centimeter\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mrow><msup><mrow><mstyle><mrow><mtext>nmol cm</mtext></mrow></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></math></span></span>)</p>\n\t\t\t<span class=\"formatted_line_break delivery_mode:Both text-center\"></span>\n\n\t\t\t<p class=\"text-center\">in Apples Grown with Grass Ground Cover</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col3\">\n\t\t\t<p class=\"text-center\">Concentration of Pigment</p>\n\t\t\t<span class=\"formatted_line_break delivery_mode:Both text-center\"></span>\n\n\t\t\t<p class=\"text-center\">(mean <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"plus or minus 2 S E sub x bar\"><math alttext=\"plus or minus 2 S E sub x bar\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mo>±</mo><mn>2</mn><mtext>SE</mtext></mrow><mrow><mover><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>¯</mo></mrow></mover></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> in <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"nanomoles per square centimeter\"><math alttext=\"nanomoles per square centimeter\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mrow><msup><mrow><mstyle><mrow><mtext>nmol cm</mtext></mrow></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></math></span></span>)</p>\n\t\t\t<span class=\"formatted_line_break delivery_mode:Both text-center\"></span>\n\n\t\t\t<p class=\"text-center\">in Apples Grown with Reflective Ground Cover</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr class=\"row\">\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col1 text-center\">Anthocyanins</td>\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col2 text-center\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"14.51 plus or minus 1.9\"><math alttext=\"14.51 plus or minus 1.9\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>14.51</mn><mo>±</mo><mn>1.9</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span></td>\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col3 text-center\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"24.10 plus or minus 3.0\"><math alttext=\"24.10 plus or minus 3.0\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>24.10</mn><mo>±</mo><mn>3.0</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span></td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr class=\"row\">\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col1 text-center\">Flavonoids</td>\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col2 text-center\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"29.24 plus or minus 3.6\"><math alttext=\"29.24 plus or minus 3.6\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>29.24</mn><mo>±</mo><mn>3.6</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span></td>\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col3 text-center\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"44.50 plus or minus 5.7\"><math alttext=\"44.50 plus or minus 5.7\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>44.50</mn><mo>±</mo><mn>5.7</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span></td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"item_part part_id:a part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"a\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a) Using the information provided in Figure 2, <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">explain</span> the role of light in the activation of the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P A L\"><math alttext=\"P A L\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>PAL</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> enzyme.</p>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR251773_rubric"},{"id":"VR251773","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:b part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"b\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b) <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Identify</span> the variable in the researchers' experiment that is dependent on the percent of reflected light the apple trees receive. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Justify</span> the use of genetically identical apple trees as a controlled factor in the experiment. Using the data provided, <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">describe</span> the effect of the different ground covers on the percent of light reflected. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Calculate </span>the percent change in the average concentration of flavonoids in apples grown with the reflective ground cover compared with the apples grown with the grass ground cover.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR251773_rubric"},{"id":"VR251773","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:c part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"c\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(c) Researchers also study apple trees that have been genetically modified so that the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"D N A\"><math alttext=\"D N A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>DNA</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> binding domain of the transcription factor that stimulates expression of the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P A L\"><math alttext=\"P A L\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>PAL</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> enzyme has been deleted. The researchers repeat the ground cover experiment with the genetically modified apple trees. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Predict</span> the effect of the two ground covers on pigment concentrations in the genetically modified apples. Provide reasoning to <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">justify</span> your prediction.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR251773_rubric"},{"id":"VR251773","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:d part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"d\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(d) Based on the information provided in Figure 2, <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">predict</span> the effect of a constantly active kinase on flavonoid pigment production. In leaves, the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P A L\"><math alttext=\"P A L\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>PAL</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> enzyme is also required for the production of other pigment molecules that are capable of absorbing <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U V\"><math alttext=\"U V\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>UV</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and other radiation from the sun. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Explain</span> how the relationship between light and pigment production might serve as a protective mechanism for the cells of the apple tree. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Explain</span> how the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P A L\"><math alttext=\"P A L\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>PAL</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> enzyme interacts with its substrate in the absence of light.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR251773_rubric"}]